  </section>

  <!-- Deep Dive: Each number -->
  <section style="padding:5rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-light-bg);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border);">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto xl:mx-0 xl:max-w-none">

      <div style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:3rem;">
        <p class="p-label" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">In Depth</p>
        <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:clamp(1.75rem,4vw,2.75rem);font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          What Each Life Path Number Means
        </h2>
        <div class="p-divider" style="margin:0 auto;"></div>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 1 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 1: The Pioneer</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 1 people tend to be self-starters. They have opinions, they back themselves, and they don't usually wait for permission. That can look like confidence from the outside. From the inside, it often feels more like restlessness, a low-grade frustration when things aren't moving fast enough.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          They end up in leadership roles less because they want to manage people and more because they have a clear direction and others follow it. The sticking point for most 1s is that the same drive that gets things done makes it hard to delegate or ask for help. Learning to let people in is genuinely difficult with this number. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-1/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 1 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 2 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 2: The Diplomat</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          If life path 1 is about forging ahead alone, life path 2 is about reading the room. These people notice things others miss: a shift in someone's energy, tension that nobody's naming, the thing that needs to be said to bring two people back into alignment. That's a real skill. It's also exhausting to carry.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The recurring challenge for life path 2 is that their attunement to everyone else's needs tends to come at the expense of their own. They're often the last person in the room to admit they're unhappy. Getting comfortable asserting what they actually want, not just facilitating what everyone else wants - is the work of this number. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-2/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 2 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 3 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 3: The Creator</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 3 is fundamentally about expression. These people have things to say: through writing, conversation, art, performance, or just the way they tell a story at dinner. They're often the one in the group who makes everything a bit more interesting, which is a gift as long as they don't use it to avoid the deeper work.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The pattern that shows up most often with this number is starting more than they finish. Ideas arrive fast, excitement peaks early, and then something new comes along. Discipline and follow-through don't come naturally. The 3 that has figured out how to channel their creativity into something sustained tends to do extraordinary things. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-3/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 3 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 4 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 4: The Architect</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 4 people get things done. Not with flair usually. With systems, consistency, and a quiet intolerance for cutting corners. If you need someone to actually build the thing, not just talk about it, a 4 is who you want. They do what they say they'll do. That sounds basic, but it's rarer than it should be.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The tension in this number comes from the same place as its strength. The methodical mind that builds solid foundations doesn't bend easily. When circumstances demand flexibility: a pivot, an unexpected change of direction, someone else's way of doing things - life path 4 can dig in harder than the situation warrants. The work here is learning that structure is a tool, not a principle. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-4/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 4 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 5 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 5: The Freedom Seeker</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 5 doesn't do well standing still. These people are drawn to change, novelty, and the feeling that life is still opening up rather than narrowing down. That energy is genuinely magnetic. They tend to collect experiences, stories, and interesting people wherever they go.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The shadow side is that restlessness can start working against them. Jobs, relationships, projects: the pattern is often the same: fully in, then quietly out the door when the initial excitement fades. Not because they're careless, but because routine feels like a small death to a 5. The ones who thrive are the ones who find ways to build freedom into their commitments rather than using freedom as a reason to avoid them. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-5/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 5 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 6 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 6: The Caretaker</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 6 people show up for others. Full stop. When someone in their circle is struggling, they're already working out how to help - practically, not just emotionally. They're good in a crisis, they remember people's difficult anniversaries, and they often hold communities together without anyone quite noticing.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The problem is that this same instinct, left unchecked, tips into over-responsibility. Life path 6 people have a habit of taking on other people's problems as their own, saying yes when they mean no, and ending up exhausted in service of relationships that don't fully reciprocate. The growth for this number is getting comfortable with boundaries without feeling like they've become someone cold. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-6/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 6 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 7 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 7: The Mystic</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 7 is the number that asks why. Not in an irritating way - in the way that drives real inquiry. These people are rarely satisfied with surface explanations. They'll read the book and then five more books that contradict it. They gravitate toward questions that don't have clean answers: philosophy, science, psychology, the nature of consciousness, the structure of reality.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The difficulty with this number is that a rich inner life can make ordinary social situations feel hollow. Life path 7 people sometimes withdraw rather than engage, and that isolation compounds - the less they connect, the harder connection becomes. The number 7 in numerology is associated with wisdom, but wisdom that's never tested by real relationship stays theoretical. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-7/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 7 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 8 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;padding-bottom:2.5rem;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 8: The Executive</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 8 understands how things work at scale. These people think in systems, resources, and outcomes. They're drawn to business, finance, and positions where they can actually move something significant, not just contribute to it but direct it. The ambition isn't vanity. It's how they're wired.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The blind spot that comes up most often with this number is that the drive for achievement can crowd out everything else. Relationships, health, the question of whether any of this is actually making them happy - those things get deferred. And then deferred again. Life path 8 people sometimes hit a point in their forties where they've built exactly what they set out to build and still feel empty. The number asks for more than material success. It asks for the wisdom to use it. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-8/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 8 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- LP 9 -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:0;">
        <h3 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:1.3rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path 9: The Sage</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
          Life path 9 is the last of the single-digit numbers, and it carries a quality that's hard to explain without sounding vague: a kind of broad compassion. These people often feel a strong pull toward service - not because it's expected of them, but because indifference to suffering doesn't come naturally. They can seem like old souls because, in a sense, they carry the weight of the numbers that came before theirs.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
          The recurring struggle with this number is holding on past the point of purpose. Life path 9 is thematically about completion and release - finishing what needs finishing, letting go of what's run its course. In practice, that's hard. Detachment gets mistaken for coldness. The 9 that figures out how to love fully and release gracefully is genuinely rare, and genuinely formidable. <a href="/learn/life-path-number-9/" style="color:var(--color-violet);text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Full Life Path 9 guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Life Path & Compatibility -->
  <section style="padding:5rem 1.5rem;background:white;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border);">
    <div style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;">
      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:clamp(1.75rem,4vw,2.5rem);font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 1.5rem;">
        Life Path Number &amp; Relationships
      </h2>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 1rem;">
        Compatibility is probably the most common reason people look up their life path number after finding out what it is. It's a reasonable instinct: if the number says something real about how you operate, it probably says something real about who you clash with and who you don't.
      </p>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 1rem;">
        As a rough framework: even-numbered life paths (2, 4, 6, 8) tend to want stability and continuity in relationships. Odd-numbered paths (1, 3, 5, 7, 9) tend to need more room and stimulation. Those two orientations can absolutely work together, but they'll produce predictable friction if neither person understands what the other actually needs.
      </p>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 2rem;">
        That said, the life path number alone isn't enough for a serious compatibility reading. Your expression number, soul urge number, and personal year cycle all feed into the picture. It's worth getting a full reading rather than deciding compatibility on one number.
      </p>
      <a href="/learn/compatibility/" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;background:transparent;color:var(--color-body-text);font-weight:600;font-size:0.95rem;padding:0.875rem 1.75rem;border-radius:6px;text-decoration:none;border:1.5px solid var(--color-border);">Explore Compatibility Checker →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Life Path & Career -->
  <section style="padding:5rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-light-bg);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border);">
    <div style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;">
      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:clamp(1.75rem,4vw,2.5rem);font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 1.5rem;">
        Life Path Number &amp; Career Path
      </h2>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 1rem;">
        Career is where the life path number gets practically interesting. Because it describes how you're wired rather than what you're good at, it tends to point toward environments where you'll sustain motivation, not just environments where you can technically perform.
      </p>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 1rem;">
        Life paths 1 and 8 usually do well in roles with real autonomy and measurable outcomes: entrepreneurship, leadership, anything where their strategic instincts get used rather than suppressed. Life paths 2 and 6 tend to find work in people-centred fields more sustainable: counselling, teaching, healthcare, mediation. The emotional intelligence they bring to those roles isn't a soft skill. It's the thing.
      </p>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0 0 1rem;">
        Life path 3 people often end up in writing, marketing, speaking, or creative work, sometimes despite a very different career plan. Life path 7 gravitates toward research, analysis, or anything that rewards going deep on something. Life path 9, with its pull toward broader service, frequently finds its way into the arts, advocacy, or healing professions.
      </p>
      <p style="color:var(--color-muted-text);line-height:1.8;margin:0;">
        None of this is prescriptive. What the number describes is where you'll find it easier to stay engaged, and where you're likely to feel like something is wrong even when everything looks right on paper.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section style="padding:5rem 1.5rem;background:white;border-top:1px solid var(--color-border);">
    <div style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;">
      <div style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:3rem;">
        <p class="p-label" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">Common Questions</p>
        <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-family-heading);font-size:clamp(1.75rem,4vw,2.75rem);font-weight:700;color:var(--color-body-text);margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Life Path Number FAQ</h2>
        <div class="p-divider" style="margin:0 auto;"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">

        <details>
          <summary>What is my life path number?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Add up your birth date in three separate pieces: day, month, and year. Reduce each piece to a single digit (or stop at 11 or 22 if you hit those). Then add the three results together and reduce again. Whatever you land on, a number from 1 to 9, or one of the master numbers 11, 22, 33, that's your life path number.</div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Which date of birth is powerful in numerology?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Every birth date carries its own distinctive energy. There's no objectively "most powerful" date in numerology. However, birth dates that produce master numbers (11, 22, or 33) are considered to carry exceptional potential and spiritual responsibility. What matters most is how aligned you are with the energy of your own number, not where it ranks against others.</div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>What is the rarest life path number?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Master number 33. It only appears when the birth date totals exactly 33, which requires a very specific combination of day, month, and year. Master number 22 is the next rarest, then 11. Among the single-digit numbers, 8 and 7 tend to be slightly less common statistically. The rarity isn't what makes a number significant.</div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Why is number 7 so powerful in numerology?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Number 7 in numerology represents the search for truth, deep knowledge, and spiritual understanding. It sits at the intersection of the practical and the mystical. Cultures throughout history have treated 7 as sacred, seven days of the week, seven musical notes, seven colours of the rainbow. Life path 7 people are often drawn to science, philosophy, and spiritual practice precisely because their essence is to understand, not just to do.</div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Can my life path number change?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">No. It's calculated from your birth date, which doesn't change. Name-based numbers like your expression number or soul urge number can shift if you change your legal name, but the life path number stays the same regardless of anything you do. That permanence is one of the main reasons practitioners treat it as the most foundational number in a chart.</div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Is the life path number the same as a birthday number?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">No. These are two different numbers in numerology. Your birthday number is simply the day of the month you were born, reduced to a single digit if necessary. Your life path number uses your complete date of birth (day, month, and full year) reduced through a specific method. The birthday number is a supporting influence; the life path number represents your overarching life theme and purpose.</div>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>What's the difference between the life path number and a karmic debt number?<svg class="faq-chevron" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">A karmic debt number arises when certain numbers appear in your chart: specifically 13, 14, 16, and 19. If your life path number is reached via one of these before final reduction (e.g., your total is 13 before reducing to 4), you carry a karmic debt overlay. The life path number describes your overarching purpose; the karmic debt number describes an additional layer of challenge and growth woven into it.</div>
        </details>

      </div>
    </div>
